                    [0-12609] heading: Measuring the quantum W state: Seeing a trio of entangled photons in one go
                    [0-13369] paragraph
                      [0-13370] StaticText: by
                      [0-13371] link: Kyoto University
                    [0-13373] div
                      [0-13374] div
                        [0-13376] StaticText: edited by
                        [0-13377] link: Sadie Harley
                        [0-13379] StaticText: , reviewed by
                        [0-13380] link: Robert Egan
                      [0-13389] button: Editors' notes
                        [0-13390] image
                    [0-13420] div
                      [0-13423] figure
                        [0-13424] image: Measuring the quantum W state
                        [0-13425] Figcaption
                          [0-13426] StaticText: Achieving the entanglement measurement of the W state. Credit: KyotoU / Takeuchi lab
                      [0-13427] paragraph
                        [0-13428] StaticText: The concept of quantum entanglement is emblematic of the gap between classical and quantum physics. Referring to a situation in which it is impossible to describe the physics of each photon separately, this key characteristic of quantum mechanics defies the classical expectation that each particle should have a reality of its own, which gravely concerned Einstein.
                      [0-13433] paragraph
                        [0-13434] StaticText: Understanding the potential of this concept is essential for the realization of powerful new quantum technologies.
                      [0-13435] paragraph
                        [0-13436] StaticText: Developing such technologies will require the ability to freely generate a multi-
                        [0-13437] link: photon
                        [0-13439] StaticText: quantum
                        [0-13440] link: entangled state
                        [0-13442] StaticText: , and then to efficiently identify what kind of entangled state is present. However, when performing conventional quantum tomography, a method commonly used for state estimation, the number of measurements required grows exponentially with the number of photons, posing a significant data collection problem.
                      [0-13443] paragraph
                        [0-13444] StaticText: If available, an entangled measurement can identify the entangled state with a one-shot approach. Such a measurement for the Greenberger-Horne-Zeilinger‚ÄîGHZ‚Äîentangled
                        [0-13445] link: quantum state
                        [0-13447] StaticText: has been realized, but for the W state, the other representative entangled multi-photon state, it has been neither proposed nor discovered experimentally.
                      [0-13448] paragraph
                        [0-13449] StaticText: This motivated a team of researchers at Kyoto University and Hiroshima University to take on this challenge, ultimately succeeding in developing a new method of entangled measurement to identify the W state. The paper is
                        [0-13450] link: published
                        [0-13452] StaticText: in the journal
                        [0-13454] StaticText: Science Advances
                        [0-13455] StaticText: .
                      [0-13456] paragraph
                        [0-13457] StaticText: "More than 25 years after the initial proposal concerning the entangled measurement for GHZ states, we have finally obtained the entangled measurement for the W state as well, with genuine experimental demonstration for 3-photon W states," says corresponding author Shigeki Takeuchi.
                      [0-13461] insertion
                        [0-13463] Iframe: Advertisement
                      [0-13466] paragraph
                        [0-13467] StaticText: The team focused on the characteristics of the W state's cyclic shift symmetry, and theoretically proposed a method to create an entangled measurement using a photonic quantum circuit that performs quantum Fourier transformation for the W state of any number of photons.
                      [0-13468] paragraph
                        [0-13469] StaticText: They created a device to demonstrate the proposed method for three photons using high-stability optical quantum circuits, which allowed the device to operate stably without active control for an extended period of time.
                      [0-13470] paragraph
                        [0-13471] StaticText: By inserting three single photons into the device in appropriate polarization states, the team was able to demonstrate that the device can distinguish different types of three-photon W states, each corresponding to a specific non-classical correlation between the three input photons.
                      [0-13472] paragraph
                        [0-13473] StaticText: The researchers were able to evaluate the fidelity of the entangled measurement, which is equal to the probability of obtaining the correct result for a pure W-state input.
                      [0-13474] paragraph
                        [0-13475] StaticText: This achievement opens the door for quantum teleportation, or the transfer of quantum information. It could also lead to new quantum communication protocols, the transfer of multi-photon quantum entangled states, and new methods for measurement-based quantum computing.
                      [0-13476] paragraph
                        [0-13477] StaticText: "In order to accelerate the research and development of quantum technologies, it is crucial to deepen our understanding of basic concepts to come up with innovative ideas," says Takeuchi.
                      [0-13478] paragraph
                        [0-13479] StaticText: In the future, the team aims to apply their method to a larger-scale, more general multi-photon quantum entangled state, and plans to develop on-chip photonic quantum circuits for entangled measurements.
                      [0-13480] div
                        [0-13481] paragraph
                          [0-13482] strong
                            [0-13483] StaticText: More information:

**ELIGIBILITY FOR CHILD BENEFIT:**
- You normally qualify if you're responsible for a child under 16 and live in the UK

- For children 16+ but under 20: You can still qualify if they stay in approved education or training
- Special circumstances covered: fostering, adoption, looking after someone else's child, living abroad in certain cases
- EU Settlement Scheme holders have specific eligibility rules based on their status and circumstances

**HOW CHILD BENEFIT WORKS:**
- An allowance paid for each child (usually every 4 weeks)
- National Insurance credits that count towards your State Pension
- Automatic National Insurance number for your child before they turn 16
- You can claim even if you don't want payments (still get other benefits like NI credits)
- Protects your State Pension by filling gaps in NI record if you're not working or don't earn enough

**PAYMENT AMOUNTS:**
- Eldest or only child: ¬£26.05 per week
- Additional children: ¬£17.25 per child per week
- High Income Child Benefit Charge applies if you or your partner earn over the threshold

- Can claim 48 hours after registering birth or when child comes to live with you
- Can be backdated up to 3 months from claim date
- PRIMARY METHOD: Apply online (Start now button available)
- Alternative methods: by post or by phone
- What you need: child's birth/adoption certificate (if available), bank details, your NI number, partner's NI number
- Can claim without birth certificate but takes longer
- For children born outside UK: need original certificate and passport/travel document

## Comprehensive Comparison: Afghan Hound vs. Akita vs. Azawakh

### **Origins & History**
- **Afghan Hound**: Ancient breed from mountainous regions, recognized by AKC in 1926
- **Akita**: Ancient Japanese breed developed in 17th century Japan, recognized by AKC in 1972  
- **Azawakh**: West African sighthound from Burkina Faso, Mali, and Niger, newest breed recognized by AKC in 2019

### **Size & Physical Characteristics**
- **Afghan Hound**: 25-27" tall, 50-60 lbs, thick silky flowing coat, elegant sighthound build
- **Akita**: 24-28" tall, 70-130 lbs, muscular spitz-type with double coat, very substantial build
- **Azawakh**: 23.5-29" tall, 33-55 lbs, extremely lean with visible bone structure, short fine coat

### **Breed Groups & Purpose**
- **Afghan Hound**: Hound Group - Sighthound bred for hunting with speed and keen vision
- **Akita**: Working Group - Family protector and guardian, symbol of good health and happiness in Japan
- **Azawakh**: Hound Group - Sighthound companion, guardian, and lure courser

### **Temperament**
- **Afghan Hound**: Independent / Sweet - Aloof and dignified but can be silly and loyal
- **Akita**: Dignified / Courageous / Profoundly Loyal - Quiet, fastidious, wary of strangers
- **Azawakh**: Independent / Loyal / Deeply Affectionate - Fiercely independent with amazing dignity

### **Exercise & Activity Needs**
- **Afghan Hound**: HIGH - Needs opportunity to run full out several times weekly, not suitable off-leash
- **Akita**: MODERATE - Daily jog or brisk walk, not highly active but enjoys energetic play
- **Azawakh**: HIGH - Active breed requiring daily exercise, excellent running companions

### **Training & Intelligence** 
- **Afghan Hound**: Independent nature, basic commands sufficient, hunting instinct cannot be trained out
- **Akita**: Very intelligent but headstrong, requires consistent training from puppyhood and extensive socialization
- **Azawakh**: Highly intelligent and fiercely independent, needs early positive training, does not respond to harsh methods

### **Grooming Requirements**
- **Afghan Hound**: HIGH - Several hours weekly brushing needed, regular bathing with conditioner
- **Akita**: MODERATE - Weekly brushing, seasonal heavy shedding ("blowing coat" twice yearly)
- **Azawakh**: LOW - Minimal upkeep, weekly brush with soft bristle, infrequent bathing needed

### **Family Life**
All three breeds share similar family characteristics:
- Independent with family members
- Not recommended for homes with young children
- Not recommended for homes with other dogs
- Require experienced owners

### **Health & Longevity**
- **Afghan Hound**: 12-18 years, sensitive to anesthesia, prone to bloat
- **Akita**: 10-14 years, prone to bloat, hip dysplasia, eye and thyroid disorders
- **Azawakh**: 12-15 years, generally healthy, minimal required health testing

### **Popularity & Recognition**
- **Afghan Hound**: #110 of 202 breeds (established breed with moderate popularity)
- **Akita**: #59 of 202 breeds (more popular, well-known breed)  
- **Azawakh**: #192 of 202 breeds (very rare, newest AKC breed)

### **Best Suited For:**
- **Afghan Hound**: Experienced owners wanting an elegant, independent sighthound who can commit to extensive grooming
- **Akita**: Experienced owners seeking a loyal guardian dog with moderate exercise needs and strong protective instincts
- **Azawakh**: Active experienced owners wanting a rare, athletic sighthound companion with minimal grooming needs

## Comprehensive Comparison: Afghan Hound vs. Akita vs. Azawakh

### **Origins & History**
- **Afghan Hound**: Ancient breed from mountainous regions, recognized by AKC in 1926
- **Akita**: Ancient Japanese breed developed in 17th century Japan, recognized by AKC in 1972  
- **Azawakh**: West African sighthound from Burkina Faso, Mali, and Niger, newest breed recognized by AKC in 2019

### **Size & Physical Characteristics**
- **Afghan Hound**: 25-27" tall, 50-60 lbs, thick silky flowing coat, elegant sighthound build
- **Akita**: 24-28" tall, 70-130 lbs, muscular spitz-type with double coat, very substantial build
- **Azawakh**: 23.5-29" tall, 33-55 lbs, extremely lean with visible bone structure, short fine coat

### **Breed Groups & Purpose**
- **Afghan Hound**: Hound Group - Sighthound bred for hunting with speed and keen vision
- **Akita**: Working Group - Family protector and guardian, symbol of good health and happiness in Japan
- **Azawakh**: Hound Group - Sighthound companion, guardian, and lure courser

### **Temperament**
- **Afghan Hound**: Independent / Sweet - Aloof and dignified but can be silly and loyal
- **Akita**: Dignified / Courageous / Profoundly Loyal - Quiet, fastidious, wary of strangers
- **Azawakh**: Independent / Loyal / Deeply Affectionate - Fiercely independent with amazing dignity

### **Exercise & Activity Needs**
- **Afghan Hound**: HIGH - Needs opportunity to run full out several times weekly, not suitable off-leash
- **Akita**: MODERATE - Daily jog or brisk walk, not highly active but enjoys energetic play
- **Azawakh**: HIGH - Active breed requiring daily exercise, excellent running companions

### **Training & Intelligence** 
- **Afghan Hound**: Independent nature, basic commands sufficient, hunting instinct cannot be trained out
- **Akita**: Very intelligent but headstrong, requires consistent training from puppyhood and extensive socialization
- **Azawakh**: Highly intelligent and fiercely independent, needs early positive training, does not respond to harsh methods

### **Grooming Requirements**
- **Afghan Hound**: HIGH - Several hours weekly brushing needed, regular bathing with conditioner
- **Akita**: MODERATE - Weekly brushing, seasonal heavy shedding ("blowing coat" twice yearly)
- **Azawakh**: LOW - Minimal upkeep, weekly brush with soft bristle, infrequent bathing needed

### **Family Life**
All three breeds share similar family characteristics:
- Independent with family members
- Not recommended for homes with young children
- Not recommended for homes with other dogs
- Require experienced owners

### **Health & Longevity**
- **Afghan Hound**: 12-18 years, sensitive to anesthesia, prone to bloat
- **Akita**: 10-14 years, prone to bloat, hip dysplasia, eye and thyroid disorders
- **Azawakh**: 12-15 years, generally healthy, minimal required health testing

### **Popularity & Recognition**
- **Afghan Hound**: #110 of 202 breeds (established breed with moderate popularity)
- **Akita**: #59 of 202 breeds (more popular, well-known breed)  
- **Azawakh**: #192 of 202 breeds (very rare, newest AKC breed)

### **Best Suited For:**
- **Afghan Hound**: Experienced owners wanting an elegant, independent sighthound who can commit to extensive grooming
- **Akita**: Experienced owners seeking a loyal guardian dog with moderate exercise needs and strong protective instincts
- **Azawakh**: Active experienced owners wanting a rare, athletic sighthound companion with minimal grooming needs

All three breeds require experienced dog owners due to their independent natures and are not recommended for first-time dog owners or families with young children.

## Gluten-Free Diet Guidelines for Pregnant Women

**Folate (600mcg daily):**
- Spinach (131 mcg in ¬Ω cup cooked)

- Kidney beans (46 mcg in ¬Ω cup)

- Spinach (6mg in 1 cup cooked)

**Calcium (1000mg daily):**
- Plain low-fat yogurt (415mg per cup)
- Milk or fortified soy milk (276-299mg per cup)
- Part-skim mozzarella cheese (333mg in 1.5 ounces)

**Fiber (25g daily):**
- Legumes (10-16g per cup cooked)
- Brown rice (3.5g in 1 cup cooked)
- Fruits and vegetables
- Nuts (3g in 1 ounce)

**Breakfast:**
- Quinoa breakfast bowl with almond milk, berries, bananas, nuts, and honey
- Vegetable omelet with spinach, bell peppers, mushrooms

**Lunch:**
- Grilled chicken salad with mixed greens, tomatoes, cucumber, avocado
- Quinoa stuffed bell peppers with black beans, corn, tomatoes

**Dinner:**
- Baked salmon with roasted vegetables (carrots, Brussels sprouts, sweet potatoes)
- Gluten-free pasta with steamed vegetables and olive oil

**Snacks:**
- Greek yogurt parfait with gluten-free granola and fruit
- Rice cakes with nut butter

### Foods to Avoid:
- All wheat, barley, rye products
- Regular bread, pasta, crackers, cereals
- Beer and malt beverages
- Many processed foods (check labels carefully)

### Key Recommendations:
1. Take a gluten-free prenatal vitamin
2. Work with a registered dietitian specializing in celiac disease
3. Focus on whole, naturally gluten-free foods

                  [0-4874] heading: About the project
                  [0-4879] div
                    [0-4880] paragraph
                      [0-4881] StaticText: The Jamaica Bus Depot was built in 1939, and the facility lacks the appropriate maintenance facilities to service the current fleet size. The new depot will also allow the MTA to transition to a fully electric bus fleet, which will eliminate carbon emissions associated with diesel fuel exhaust, resulting in cleaner air for Queens residents.
                    [0-4882] list
                      [0-4883] listitem
                        [4884] ListMarker: ‚Ä¢
                        [0-4885] StaticText: The project will include a permanent art installation, funded through the MTA Arts & Design Percent for Art program. The selection of both artist and art medium is underway. More information about MTA Arts & Design can be found
                        [0-4886] link: here
                        [0-4888] StaticText: .
                      [0-4889] listitem
                        [4890] ListMarker: ‚Ä¢
                        [0-4891] StaticText: The design of the new facility incorporates new sustainability components. The depot building will have a ‚Äúgreen roof,‚Äù which will not only help clean the air and absorb stormwater, but also act a form of insulation and reduce the depot‚Äôs energy use. The depot is being constructed in accordance with LEED certification standards, an accredited and globally recognized status of sustainability achievement in construction.
                      [0-4892] listitem
                        [4893] ListMarker: ‚Ä¢
                        [0-4894] StaticText: The design of the new bus depot will address residents‚Äô concerns about noise by erecting a sound-deadening barrier wall along 107th Avenue and another along 165th Street. The walls will shield residents from noise produced by bus depot operations as well as create a visual barrier from the depot itself.
                      [0-4895] listitem
                        [4896] ListMarker: ‚Ä¢
                        [0-4897] StaticText: To achieve the MTA‚Äôs goal of creating economic opportunity in the communities where construction projects take place, we are piloting our first-ever local hiring goals, striving to recruit 20% of the New York State workforce from neighborhoods in Southeast Queens. As of October 2023, the project was on its way to achieving its M/WBE and SDVOB targets, and in some categories the project has already surpassed them.
                        [0-4898] list
                          [0-4899] listitem
                            [4900] ListMarker: ‚ó¶
                            [0-4901] StaticText: Skanska, the project‚Äôs contractor, employs an Outreach Coordinator whose job is to ensure best-faith efforts to contract with M/WBE and SDVOB firms for smaller contracts within the larger project. Skanska is also participating in events such as internship fairs and other community outreach events to provide opportunities for Jamaica, Queens residents.
